      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>678 threads, <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=0>1</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=25>2</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=50>3</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=75>4</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=100>5</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=125>6</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=150>7</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=175>8</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=200>9</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=225>10</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=250>11</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=275>12</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=300>13</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=325>14</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=350>15</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=375>16</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=400>17</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=425>18</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=450>19</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=475>20</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=500>21</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=525>22</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=550>23</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=575>24</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=600>25</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=625>26</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=650>27</a> <a href=classes.html?class=7&start=675>28</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;<a href=classes.html?class=7&start=25>Next Page</a></td></tr></table></form><a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7>Root thread</a><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96808908415178></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96808908415178><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>A few things to do when it is time to run . . . .</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1032><span id= >Ebonygem</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Sep 4th 1:38 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There will come a point in some battles when it is time to flee.&nbsp;&nbsp;As the group's cleric you have a number of ways to help - not just save yourself, but help save others in your group.  It should be noted at the outset that trying to help your group mates is going to mean you will occationally die when you might have been able to save yourself.  While this is regretable, it is one way you show you can be trusted to work in difficult and dangerous situtaions.  Being the first (and maybe only) person to save themselves too often is not so good for your reputaion.  That being said, here are some things I find effective in times of trouble. <br><br>First idea:  the tanks should be fighting a delaying action while the casters flee.  While they do this, you must begin to move towards the zone.  Do not stay in contact with the MOBs but do not zone either.  One of our jobs as the cleric is to 'pick up' the fighters as they get beaten up.  Move to distant healing range (but towards the zone) and be prepared to heal the most wounded of the fighters.  Be most concerned if the tank drops below one bubble of health since his movement and defense will be impacted.  Sometimes it will be better to cast two or three less efficient healing spells to keep each of the tanks moving at full speed rather than casting your biggest healing spell once.  Often this will lead to the MOB beating on you - if so - it becomes the tank's job to taunt it off of you rather than zone.  If you and your tank(s) trust each other and can learn to work together, many deaths can be avoided.<br><br>Second idea:  you will often find that you can attract the attention of every (or at least most) of the critters by casting a big healing spell.  This can be used to get everybody safely out IF the group knows what you are planing and runs rather than try to 'save' you.  The tough part of this strategy is making sure everybody knows and follows the plan.  (Which means it is a good idea talk this over while people are meditating.)  When you cast that last heal and get the attention of all the MOBs - the party should flee towards the zone.  Give them a few seconds to run if you can and then cast divine aura.  With a cost of 10 mana and its 1.0 casting time - you will almost always be able to get the spell off.  Keep in mind that divine aura has an 'anti-taunt' effect which can send the MOBs chasing after the party - that is why you wait a few seconds to give them a head start before you cast it.  As above, people that can survive a few hits should stay in zone to help you out.   Even using your Divine Aura, you may need a bit of help to make it safely to the zone.<br><br>Third idea:  one other way to use your healing taunt to good effect is when a group gate or evac is being cast.  This works really well if there are two healers who can keep the MOBs bouncing back and forth between the healers as they heal each other.  I will normally cast my biggest healing spell as soon as it becomes clear they party is going to evacuate.  I would much rather the critters hit on me rather than disrupt the casting of the wizard or druid.  Take great care if you need to use divine aura in this situation.  If you don't take the divine aura off before the evac goes off - you will be left behind and almost surely die.<br><br>Fourth idea:  crowd contol spells like root or fear or atone can be helpful from time to time.  However since you are running for the zone, it is important to keep in mind the goal is to get everybody across the line alive.  A slow casting/slow recycling, high cost spell like atone is rarely the thing to cast.  Fear can work, but the MOBs do not always run away the way you think they will - you can actually make things worse with a successful fear spell.  I think that root works best in this situation; it is low cost in terms of mana, doesn't tend to draw in new critters and gets the job done cleanly.  Normally, the root lasts more than long enough to get everyone safely out.  There are a few things to beware of if you use crowd control techinques to help you flee.  Sometimes, seeing only one mob chasing them, half the party decides that battle can now be won and stops to fight.  (Forgetting the other mobs you rooted around the last corner are going to be coming back very soon.)  Othertimes, you will wish you had that mana back for healing.  Healing always works (save for fizzles), while spells cast on mobs can be resisted. <br><br>One last thought:  the time to flee isn't when everybody is out of mana and half dead.  If things have gotten to that point there are very few things you can do besides run.  A key part of your job as the cleric is to see when things are going to go wrong and get everybody headed to the zone while more options are open to you.  If the party gets started out of the zone / towards the guards before things get desparate, not only do people survive more often - but you have less down time.  Mana and health spent fighting a losing battle are wasted.  Avoiding fighting a losing battle is the best way of all to keep out of trouble.<br><br>May Innoruuk bless your efforts,<br><br><br><br>Ebonygem Val`Sharess - - RZ<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
